metadata.name: Multi-Biome #66
metadata.description:
Inspired by Jose Margulis's "Alpine Landscape"

Designed to be viewed as if you're walking past on the gallery wall, Multi-Biome is an interative play on perspective and scale. Each landscape is created from between 50 and 200 planes, slicing the landscape along a single axis.

Click and drag to rotate.

Press "s" in live view to save a png.

metadata.name: Farbteiler #119
metadata.description: Each Farbteiler is a rectilinear, mostly self-avoiding walk, dividing the space of the canvas with dotted grids using colors from Johannes Itten's Farbkreis. Everything is inside and everything is outside.

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #51
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #47
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #123
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: Morixels Colab #5 Gango #95
metadata.description:
The Gango collection was created from famous western symbols so that the whole world knows it.
In this collection, you can see a combination of unrelated but beautiful components.

Try your luck to have a more beautiful combination

The Gango is unique random Generated 200 PFP NFTs. The number of Traits in this collection is 9 (72 layers) and it has the ability to make unique 74,027,520 NFTs.

To create balance, these NFTs are randomly minted, and this is a chance for everyone to get a rare version. So due to the low price of these NFTs, if the rare version did not belong to you, it is still possible for you to mint the new NFTs.

Because this is an NFT in PFP format, you can put it on your avatar on Twitter or Instagram.

metadata.name: Fractured Time #22
metadata.description:
Composed of bent shards and twisted slivers, Fractured Time is an exploration of how we might visually perceive gravity's effects on linear time.

Like an astronaut who gets too close to a blackhole, how would we make sense of this four-dimensional time-space experience? The pieces of the world as we know it would no longer align. Everything would stretch, splinter, pulse, and fray around us.

This is my attempt to capture that mind-bending trip in two dimensions.

Press [s] to save a .png at 4000 x 4000 pixels
Press [f] to open fullscreen

32 Color Palettes
